  "prompt": "In genetics, what is an example of a monohybrid cross offspring?",
  "response": "A **monohybrid cross** involves the study of the inheritance of a single trait by crossing two organisms that differ in that particular trait. This type of cross helps to understand how one gene with two alleles is inherited from each parent to their offspring.\n\n**Example: Pea Plant Flower Color**\n\nGregor Mendel's classic experiments with pea plants provide a fundamental example of a monohybrid cross. Let's consider the trait of flower color, where:\n- **Purple flowers (P)** are dominant.\n- **White flowers (p)** are recessive.\n\n**Parental Generation (P):**\n- **Parent 1:** Homozygous dominant (PP) \u2013 purple flowers.\n- **Parent 2:** Homozygous recessive (pp) \u2013 white flowers.\n\n**Cross:** PP (purple) \u00d7 pp (white)\n\n**F\u2081 Generation:**\n- All offspring receive one allele from each parent, resulting in the genotype Pp.\n- **Phenotype:** All F\u2081 plants have purple flowers because the dominant allele (P) masks the recessive allele (p).\n\n**F\u2082 Generation (Self-crossing F\u2081 individuals):**\n- When two heterozygous F\u2081 plants (Pp) are crossed, the possible allele combinations in the offspring can be represented using a Punnett square:\n\n```\n     P    p\n   ----------\nP | PP | Pp |\n   ----------\np | Pp | pp |\n   ----------\n```\n\n- **Genotypic Ratio:** 1 PP : 2 Pp : 1 pp\n- **Phenotypic Ratio:** 3 Purple flowers : 1 White flower\n\n**Outcome:**\n- Approximately 75% of the F\u2082 generation will display purple flowers, and 25% will display white flowers.\n\nThis monohybrid cross illustrates how a single gene with two alleles segregates and how dominant and recessive traits are inherited across generations.",
